â growled Brother Archangias, as he reseated himself at the dinner table.
He fell greedily upon his bacon, and swallowed his potatoes whole instead of bread.
La Teuse, however, could not persuade Desiree to finish her dinner.
That big baby was lost in ecstasy over the nestlings, asking questions, wanting to know what food they ate, if they laid eggs, and how the cockbirds could be known.
The old servant, however, was troubled by a suspicion, and taking her stand on her sound leg, she looked the young cure in the face.
âSo you know the Paradou people?
â she said.
Thereupon he simply told the truth, relating the visit he had paid to old Jeanbernat.
La Teuse exchanged scandalised glances with Brother Archangias.
At first she answered nothing, but went round and round the table, limping frantically and stamping hard enough with her heels to split the flooring.
âYou might have spoken to me of those people these three months past,â said the priest at last.
âI should have known at any rate what sort of people I was going to call upon.
â
La Teuse stopped short as if her legs had just broken.
âDonât tell falsehoods, Monsieur le Cure,â she stuttered, âdonât tell them; you will only make your sin still worse.
How dare you say I havenât spoken to you of the Philosopher, that heathen who is the scandal of the whole neighbourhood?
The truth is, you never listen to me when I talk.
It all goes in at one ear and out at the other.
Ah, if you did listen to me, youâd spare yourself a good deal of trouble!
â
âI, too, have spoken to you about those abominations,â affirmed the Brother.
Abbe Mouret lightly shrugged his shoulders.
âWell, I didnât remember it,â he said.
