XIII
On entering the church Abbe Mouret found nine or ten big girls awaiting him with boughs of ivy, laurel, and rosemary.
Few garden flowers grew on the rocks of Les Artaud, so the custom was to decorate the Lady altar with a greenery which might last throughout the month of May.
Thereto La Teuse would add a few wallflowers whose stems were thrust into old decanters.
âWill you let me do it, Monsieur le Cure?
â she asked.
âYou are not used to it---- Come, stand there in front of the altar.
You can tell me if the decorations please you.
â
He consented, and it was she who really directed the arrangements.
Having climbed upon a pair of steps she bullied the girls as they came up to her in turn with their leafy contributions.
âNot so fast, now!
You must give me time to fix the boughs.
We canât have all these bundles coming down on his reverenceâs head---- Come on, Babet, itâs your turn.
Whatâs the good of staring at me like that with your big eyes?
Fine rosemary yours is, my word!
