And as his health returned, he hungered for keener sensations.
He now spent hours in gazing at the verdant bough: he would have liked to see it grow, expand, and throw out its branches to his very bed.
It no longer satisfied him, but only roused desires, speaking to him as it did of all the trees whose deep-sounding call he could hear although their crests were hidden from his sight.
An endless whispering of leaves, a chattering as of running water, a fluttering as of wings, all blended in one mighty, long-drawn, quivering voice, resounded in his ears.
âWhen you are able to get up,â said Albine, âyou shall sit at the window.
You will see the lovely garden!
â
He closed his eyes and murmured gently:
âOh!
