One day she brought him a bunch of roses.
At the sight of them he was so affected that he wept.
He kissed them and went to sleep with them in his arms.
But when they faded, he felt so keenly grieved that he forbade Albine to gather any more.
He preferred her, said he, for she was as fresh and as balmy; and she never faded, her hands, her hair, her cheeks were always fragrant.
At last he himself would send her into the garden, telling her not to come back before an hour.
