His limbs were regaining the strength of adolescence, but more perceptive sensations remained unroused.
He spent whole afternoons in gazing out on the Paradou, pouting like a child that sees nought but whiteness and hears but the vibration of sounds.
He still retained the ignorance of urchinhood--his sense of touch as yet so innocent that he failed to tell Albineâs gown from the covers of the old armchairs.
His eyes still stared wonderingly; his movements still displayed the wavering hesitation of limbs which scarce knew how to reach their goal; his state was one of incipient, purely instinctive existence into which entered no knowledge of surroundings.
The man was not yet born within him.
