The sun got low, it was time to go indoors.
On reaching his room, Albine burst into tears.
From that morning forward the invalid took a short walk in the garden every day.
He went past the mulberry tree, as far as the edge of the terrace, where a wide flight of broken steps descended to the flowery parterre.
He grew accustomed to the open air, each bath of sunlight brought him fresh vigour.
A young chestnut tree, which had sprung from some fallen nut between two stones of the balustrade, burst the resin of its buds, and unfolded its leafy fans with far less vigour than he progressed.
One day, indeed, he even attempted to descend the steps, but in this his strength failed him, and he sat down among the dane-wort which had grown up between the cracks in the stone flags.
Below, to the left, he could see a small wood of roses.
It was thither that he dreamt of going.
