XVI
That morning there was great commotion in the yard at the parsonage.
The Artaud butcher had just slaughtered Matthew, the pig, in the shed.
Desiree, quite enthusiastic about it all, had held Matthewâs feet, while he was being bled, kissing him on the back that he might feel the pain of the knife less, and telling him that it was absolutely necessary that he should be killed, now that he had got so fat.
No one could cut off a gooseâs neck with a single stroke of the hatchet more unconcernedly than she could, or gash open a fowlâs throat with a pair of scissors.
However much she loved her charges, she looked upon their slaughter with great equanimity.
It was quite necessary, she would say.
It made room for the young ones who were growing up.
And that morning she was very gay.
âMademoiselle,â grumbled La Teuse every minute, âyou will end by making yourself ill.
There is no sense in working yourself up into such a state, just because a pig has been slaughtered.
You are as red as if you had been dancing a whole night.
â
But Desiree only clapped her hands and turned away and bustled about again.
La Teuse, for her part, complained that her legs were sinking under her.
Since six oâclock in the morning her big carcass had been perpetually rolling between the kitchen and the yard, for she had black puddings to make.
It was she who had whisked the blood in two large earthenware pans, and she had thought that she would never get finished, since mademoiselle was for ever calling her away for mere nothings.
It must be admitted that, at the very moment when the butcher was bleeding Matthew, Desiree had been thrilled with wild excitement, for Lisa, the cow, was about to calve.
And the girlâs delight at this had quite turned her head.
âOne goes and another comes!
â she cried, skipping and twirling round.
âCome here, La Teuse!
come here!
â
It was eleven oâclock.
Every now and then the sound of chanting was wafted from the church.
A confused murmur of doleful voices, a muttering of prayers could be heard amidst scraps of Latin pronounced in louder and clearer tones.
âCome!
oh, do come!
â repeated Desiree for the twentieth time.
âI must go and toll the bell, now,â muttered the old servant.
âI shall never get finished really.
What is it that you want now, mademoiselle?
â
